---
layout: layouts/single.njk
pagination:
  data: posts
  size: 1
  alias: post
---
{{ post.content.rendered | safe }}

<hr />
{%- for item in pagination.items %}
  {% if item._embedded and item._embedded["wp:featuredmedia"] and item._embedded["wp:featuredmedia"][0] %}
    <img src="{{ item._embedded['wp:featuredmedia'][0].source_url }}" alt="{{ item.title.rendered | striptags }}" />
  {% endif %}
{% endfor -%}

Nothing in your project “calls” blog-single.njk. It’s the other way around.

blog-single.njk is an Eleventy input template. With your config, Eleventy’s dir.input is ".", so it picks up all supported templates in the project root (and under pages/, etc.). When Eleventy runs, it finds blog-single.njk, runs its pagination (one page per post), and for each page it uses the layout specified in that file’s front matter.

So:

Nothing calls blog-single.njk — Eleventy discovers it automatically as a root-level .njk file.
blog-single.njk uses a layout — its front matter has layout: layouts/single.njk, so it “calls” (wraps with) _includes/layouts/single.njk for each generated blog post page.
In short: blog-single.njk is an entry template that Eleventy runs; it then pulls in layouts/single.njk for the HTML wrapper.